{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὁπότε</b>, <br /> <i>Epic dialect</i> <b>ὁππότε</b>, both in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Ionic dialect</i> <b>ὁκότε</b>; Cyrenaic <b>ὁπόκᾰ</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Berl.Sitzb.” 1927.164 \">Refs</a>]; in <i>Doric dialect</i> Poets <b>ὁππόκᾰ</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 5.98: \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] <i>adverb</i> of Time, correlated to πότε, used much like{ὅτε}, except that the sense is less definite [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.6.3), though the two were frequently used without distinction: \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> Relat., with the <i>indicative</i>, mostly with reference to the past, <b>when,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.399, 3.173, etc.; the _indicative_ ἦστε is omitted, 8.230: in Class. _Attic dialect_ Prose only ὅτε is so used, when referring to a particular time, but later ὁπότε returns, as ὁπότε περιῆν\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] <b>when</b> she was alive, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “POxy.” 243.10 (1st c.AD)\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: with the <i>present</i> in a simile, ὡς δ᾽ ὁπότε.. ποταμὸς πεδίονδε κάτεισι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.492 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>subjunctive</i>, like{ὁπόταν}, with reference to an <i>indefinite</i> number of occasions in the <i>present</i> or to the future, ὁππότ᾽ Ἀχαιοὶ Τρώων ἐκπέρσωσ᾽ εὖ ναιόμενον πτολίεθρον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.163, compare 13.817, 21.112, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.170, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 782: sometimes in similes, ὡς ὁπότε νέφεα Ζέφυρος στυφελίξῃ 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.305, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.335 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; but ὁπότ᾽ ἄν, <i>Epic dialect</i> ὁπότε or ὁππότε κεν, is more common with <i>subjunctive</i>, and in <i>Attic dialect</i> Prose ἄν must be used, see at {ὁπόταν}: Cyrenaic ὁπόκα κα δήληται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Berl.Sitzb.” [prev. cited] \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3> with <i>optative</i>: <br /><Level4><b>__I.2.a</b></Level4> to express an event that occurred often, ὁπότε Κρήτηθεν ἵκοιτο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.233, compare 10.189, 15.284, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.591, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.99, 2.15, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 220a, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 3.4.28. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__I.2.b</b></Level4> after a verb of waiting, of a time future relatively to the past, ἷζε.. δέγμενος ὁππότε ναῦφιν ἀφορμηθεῖεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.794, compare 4.334, 7.415, 9.191, 18.524. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__I.2.c</b></Level4> in indirect speech, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 824 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 4.6.20 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; in implied indirect speech, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 24.344 (of a past promise) \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἀποδοτέον.. ὁ. μανεὶς ἀπαιτοῖ we were not [as you remember] to.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 332a. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__I.2.d</b></Level4> where the principal clause has an <i>optative</i>, μηδ᾽ ἀντιάσειας ἐκείνῳ ὁππότε νοστήσειε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 18.148, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 396c, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.6.3. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> in indirect questions, with <i>indicative</i>, ἦ ῥά τι ἴδμεν.. ὁππότε Τηλέμαχος νεῖτα; <b>when</b> he is to return, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.633; εἰς ὁ. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<b>by what time,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 3.99: rarely after a past tense, προσεδέρκετο, δέγμενος αἰεί, ὁππότε δὴ.. ἐφήσει (for ἐφείη, see above 1.2 b) 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 20.386; εἰς σὲ βλέψαι καὶ τὸν ταμίαν ὁπότ᾽ ἄριστον παραθήσει 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 613. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> ὁποτεοῦν <b>at any time whatever,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Metaphysica” 1049a1. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> in causal sense, <b>because, since,</b> with <i>indicative</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 749 (assuming variant), 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.125, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 895c, etc.; also ὁπότε γε 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1699 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 8.3.7. \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G3698","accentedUnicode":"ὁπότε","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G3697","matchingForm":"ὁποῖος","stepTransliteration":"hopoios","gloss":"what sort","_zh_tw_Gloss":"怎樣","_es_Gloss":"qué tipo","_zh_Gloss":"怎样"},{"strongNumber":"G3699","matchingForm":"ὅπου","stepTransliteration":"hopou","gloss":"where(-ever)","_zh_tw_Gloss":"那裏, 在那裏","_es_Gloss":"cuando","_zh_Gloss":"那里, 在那里"},{"strongNumber":"G3739","matchingForm":"ὅς","stepTransliteration":"hos","gloss":"which","_zh_tw_Gloss":"那一位, ...那一個","_es_Gloss":"el cual","_zh_Gloss":"那一位, ...那一个"},{"strongNumber":"G4218","matchingForm":"ποτέ","stepTransliteration":"pote","gloss":"once/when","_zh_